Let $T$ be the limb sub-tangent point with geodetic co\"ordinates
d1290 9
a1298 9
$\vec{T} = [ x_t, y_t, z_t ]^T$ be the geocentric vector to $T$, $\vec{G}$
be the outward normal at $T$, and $\vec{V}$ be a vector along the line of
sight from the instrument toward the limb tangent at $(\lambda,\phi,h)$. 
Then $\vec{N} = \vec{G} \times \vec{V}$ is normal to the plane containing
$T$, the line of sight, and the outward normal at $T$.  Let $\hat{n} =
\frac{\vec{N}}{|\vec{N}|} = [ A, B, C ]^T$ be the unit normal to that
plane.  From geometry, $\frac{C}{\sqrt{A^2+B^2}} = \cot\phi$.  Because
$|\hat{n}| = 1$, $C = \cos\phi$ and $\sqrt{A^2+B^2} = \sqrt{1-C^2} =
\sin\phi$.
